commit.message: Add Ruby 2.5, 2.6 and update Rubies on Travis CI

Add Ruby 2.3, 2.4 to Travis CI.

Update stdlib require assertions to not explode if Ruby required it before our code loaded

Eg: https://travis-ci.org/JoshCheek/thread_order/jobs/213579412

This will be necessary for https://github.com/JoshCheek/thread_order/pull/1
Bump version to 1.1.0

Revert to older style implementation

The abstractions were too much for the threads to handle :(

State Machine -- going to have to undo this

It doesn't work reliably across all implementations.
I think b/c the raise is async.
Run RSpec with colour, formatting, and have it die immediately

Extract a ResumeThread object

It observes the child and wakes or raises in the parent
at the appropriate time.

Name the worker thread so that we can look at the thread name
for any relevant thread (well... the main thread doesn't have a name, I
guess :/)

Don't expose the worker to the outside world.

Don't expose queue_size

find more side-effecty ways to test it
Add TrheadOrder#wait_until
The block receives its parent
Update gem description to mention other platforms
Expose the queue for testing, get rid of ivar access

Test the apocalypse

I dislike that I'm accessing private vars,
usually this is a sign that the behaviour is worth exposing.
Add ThreadOrder#join_all
Sync access to declared bodies

Fix bug where parent could resume without child being set

This is because the worker thread could call the enqueue block,
which then creates the child thread, but if the scheduler is letting
the child go, then the worker may not resume to assign the child.
Then, when the child wakes the parent, the scheduler may resume the parent
instead of the worker, thus the worker still has not assigned the child thread,
and the parent is resumed.

This is not a problem in prob, b/c it's due to a refactoring I just made.

The solution is to have the child thread set the variable rather than the worker thread.
Make syntax compatible with 1.8.7
Refactor implementation a bit
Don't commit Rbx bytecode
It blows up if it is waiting on another thread to sleep and that thread exits instead
Show example usage in Readme
